This interview is lightly edited for clarity.

*Topics:*

Background ( #background ) | Why Drones ( #drones ) | How a Drone Delivery =
Works ( #delivery ) | Aggregators and Restaurants ( #aggregators-restaurant=
s ) | The Manna Drone ( #manna-drone ) | Drone Regulations ( #regulations )=
 | Competition ( #competition ) | Drone-Defined Cities ( #cities )
Background

*Bobby Healy, welcome to Stratechery.*

*Bobby Healy:* It's a pleasure to be here, Ben. Thanks for having me.

*Before we get started talking about your company and drones, I want to hea=
r more about you. Tell me about your background, where you grew up, how you=
 got started in technology. Take me back to the beginning.*

*BH:* Yeah, happy to. I'm Irish born, bread and buttered, as they say. I'm =
a programmer, started my career writing video games for Nintendo, a lot of =
smash hits, the worst ever video games produced, but good fun.

*(laughing) We won't list them.*

*BH:* I was an 8-bit assembler, I'm hugely proud of them and I still have t=
he source code, which I can publish, actually. Good fun work and if I ever =
do retire I'll go back into writing video games, it's a wonderful use of yo=
ur time. So from video games to travel technology, I spent 30 years buildin=
g various different SaaS companies in the travel technology space. All boot=
strapped.

*The biggest was CarTrawler ( https://corporate.cartrawler.com/en-gb/ ) , r=
ight?*

*BH:* Yeah, CarTrawler was probably the biggest. CarTrawler was the last bu=
siness I started and it was a big one, it was a mobility aggregator for mos=
tly airlines and other online travel agencies, and I exited out twice to pr=
ivate equity, so the very boring EBITDA and margin run view of a business, =
but it was a very successful one. The travel technology space is one where =
you blend a combination of, I would say, medium travel or product and techn=
ology vision with a very legacy substrate running the infrastructure of a v=
ery large industry. So it's lipstick on a pig, largely. And my three previo=
us businesses, I've founded six businesses, but all my other businesses wer=
e all travel tech start-ups serving that were lipstick in various different=
 ways.

*So why travel? What was the allure there?*

*BH:* It's almost by accident, I fell into it. I started to build these sys=
tems where Windows, IBM OS/2 was a thing so WYSIWYG ( https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/WYSIWYG ) was the people were going from MS-DOS to user interfaces=
, and there was hundreds of thousands of travel agencies around the world t=
hat had a really terrible way to book flights for people. I mean you just m=
ainframe a 3270 terminal or an AOC terminal and you would get a list of fli=
ghts and that was how travel planning was done with travel agencies, so I w=
as building then.

I started a company in Mexico City of all places to disrupt that, to provid=
e =E2=80=94 well, then it became Windows when Windows won that war =E2=80=
=94 but a Windows interface for travel agencies to make it a little bit mor=
e rich and a little bit easier to use than a mainframe terminal. That was, =
again, when you think about it now, it seems trivial, but we essentially ha=
d to build an entire framework of Visual Basic but we wrote our own in C++ =
and our own interpreted language, kind of a C-style interpreted language to=
 allow us to do the automation, the UI automation tied to the terminal emul=
ation, and essentially automated a lot of the dumb process about searching =
travel.

Travel is no different today than it was when I started that business 35 ye=
ars ago, it still suffers from awful legacy, underpinnings, like every airl=
ine essentially using almost still assembly language-based transaction proc=
essors to do flight search availabilities, things like that.

*I mean, we're hearing similar stories with the US federal government these=
 days ( https://www.businessinsider.com/federal-retirement-pennsylvania-min=
e-paperwork-doge-musk-crosshairs-real-2025-2 ) , all these entities. It's f=
unny, it's like an infrastructure story, people will go to say like China a=
nd they'll say, "Wow, the infrastructure's amazing", and yeah, because it w=
as all built in the last 15 years.*

*BH:* Correct, correct.

*All this infrastructure and all these computer systems were amazing when t=
hey were built 50 years ago.*

*BH:* Airlines were the first industry to automate inventory and pricing, b=
ut unfortunately they're still on those systems. They still have assembly l=
anguage, 6-bit assembly language running underneath it all, and then you've=
 got all the way up the top Google Flight search that's an amazing experien=
ce, lightning fast, but man, you would not believe the infrastructure that =
they've got on top of all of that crap underneath still to make it work, bu=
t you can make money doing that. So the aggregator advantage, well, essenti=
ally you're providing technology to take advantage of their disadvantage an=
d it isn't difficult.

So you ask me why travel tech? Because it's almost like stealing candy from=
 a child. Anything you build in that space, you've got 200 hungry customers=
 that will do anything to optimize. So unlike the US government, they don't=
 still live in caves and use paper to retire people, they do want to improv=
e and it's easy to get them. It's a small community, so I love that consoli=
dation at the top of those players because, again, all my businesses were e=
nterprise SaaS businesses. Getting to your most important person in that to=
p 100 customers, super easy =E2=80=94 I like that. I like focusing on build=
ing the product, solving a problem and then the audience is very easy to fi=
nd in travel tech. So boring but rewarding, I would say.

Why Drones

*Well, if you went from boring and rewarding, was this like a midlife crisi=
s where you're like, "Look, I'm sick of putting lipstick on a pig, this is =
not sexy, let me see if I can find the sexiest possible opportunity, and th=
is time I'm going to take VC money ( https://www.independent.ie/business/te=
chnology/drone-delivery-firm-manna-aero-raises-25m/40369457.html ) , I'm go=
ing to do it totally different". I mean honestly, it's what drones sounds l=
ike.*

*BH:* First time I ever took VC money, Ben, it's the first time I've ever b=
urnt a single dollar running a business, so that's the first part. I never =
understood the VC world, I don't even know this unstructured, chaotic, pers=
onality-driven world =E2=80=94 by the way, which suits me really well, P/E =
firms and banks didn't suit me. So when I looked at this space, it wasn't t=
he old world, we didn't get into this because it's hard, we thought it was =
easy, actually we got into it because it was hard.

*Yup.*

*BH:* So I looked at this space as a natural kind of 10x or a 100x of anyth=
ing I'd ever done before. It was about scale, it wasn't about sexy, I don't=
 see this as sexy at all. I still see the numbers, I still see the basic un=
it economics, the capital economics. I see the operation, the process. Of c=
ourse I see the tech and of course I see how sexy it is and how dreamy this=
 vision is, I suppose. But it was the scale that interested me.

*Well, step back. What was your "a-ha" moment? Like, "Drones are the future=
", modern day plastics, was there a specific moment where it occurred to yo=
u?*

*BH:* There is. So you'll probably be familiar with the Irish culture and l=
iking a glass of wine or pint of Guinness or whatever, and I live in a subu=
rb of Dublin, and you're not allowed to drive anymore when you're drinking,=
 we stopped that 20 years ago in Ireland, and so it is impossible to get a =
