 last decade is they've completely changed their fulfillment center, rotati=
on center, distribution center layout to have way more locations much close=
r to lots of people. That sounds like a pretty good base to launch a bunch =
of drones from.*

*BH:* 100%. I mean, Amazon, we're not starting with parcels because it's ju=
st parcels can be solved well with the man in the van or the girl in the va=
n, that trip for latent stuff. So if you can wait half a day, then wait, bu=
t Amazon absolutely will nail this. I mean, they've obviously had false sta=
rts or bad starts, whatever, they'll get there. Amazon, just like everyone =
else in the USA, are held back by lack of, I think, scalable regulations. A=
nd we applaud them, we think they're great as well, they have a different v=
ision than us but I think they will get there.

But in the end, I think if you are only focused on one use case, you're an =
inefficient architecture, you're not taking advantage. What we're saying is=
 =E2=80=94 we want to have a meaningful commercial relationship with every =
house on the planet and that starts with something that they order every da=
y, which is coffee. We make money every time we fly a coffee, Ben, we're al=
ready margin positive on delivering something that's trivial as a coffee. S=
o I prefer that people are ordering coffees every day from us, I prefer tha=
t and maybe order a parcel every month or every two weeks.

*Yeah, the repeat customer, it's very habitual.*

*BH:* So I think Amazon will nail it. Yeah, like look at Wing's, look at Go=
ogle's aircraft ( https://wing.com/technology ) , it's a tiny aircraft that=
 carries less than a kilo or whatever, a pound-and-a-half or two pounds. Gr=
eat aircraft, reliable. But they know that it's that small thing that peopl=
e need frequently that's the first use case to solve, so we agree very much=
 on the use cases for this. There's other things we deliver, defibrillators=
, and Google are doing medicine delivery as well, there's decidedly benefic=
ial use cases. But what I'm interested in is the one that has, like I said,=
 a commercial relationship with every single household on the planet. Selli=
ng everything, bringing them everything. Maybe not selling but bringing the=
m everything.

*You keep saying scale, scale, scale. "If I could have a 100,000 drones out=
 there" =E2=80=94 can you manufacture that many drones? It feels like this =
is a looming choke point.*

*BH:* The nice thing about manufacturing is it's linear and once you know w=
hat that equation looks like you can predict it. So we have a very simple a=
ircraft to manufacture now, all of our subsystems we outsource to scalable =
vendors. So battery packs, BMS, avionics, those types of things. So scale f=
or us is really about capital and probably a lot of debt to manufacture, it=
's linear. You can use robotics, maybe it's certain things but we know the =
cost, the bill of materials of an aircraft, we know the labor that goes int=
o the aircraft, we know what parts of that labor can be automated. That isn=
't uncertain, it's hard, but it's not uncertain.

So just in the same way that Tesla scale up the Model 3 or Apple scale up t=
he iPhone, we'll do the same with drones. But the numbers required are a lo=
t less with drones because they're so productive. One of our drones does 10=
0 deliveries a day and could probably do more than that. So the number of d=
rones, like Dublin, 100 aircraft powers the entire city, 1.1 million people=
 and so if I wanted to roll out to 500 cities, whatever, what's that? 5,000=
 aircraft, it's not a lot of aircraft.

*Talking about scale and these repeatable processes, is this why you have t=
he phrase, "I'm building a tech business, not a logistics business"? Becaus=
e it's just every single thing you're focused on every single decision and =
this is sort of the Tesla analogy is scale, scale, scale, scale, scale, "I =
want to build it one time and then copy it a million times".*

*BH:* Correct, yeah. You build the perfect widget and then copy that a mill=
ion times. So it's deep tech for the first 5 years and then it's manufactur=
ing scale for the next 20 years and the product is logistics, automated log=
istics. But you would really see it, I think, as a deep tech business. You =
would see it like a Tesla, no different than a Tesla I think.

Drone-Defined Cities

*Is there a bit where you retreat to just doing the software and the hardwa=
re or what that might be? And when it comes to yes, you want to get to you =
can just fly to a business and they can attach it, but if you have these li=
ttle setups in the parking lot that shuffle coffee through, is that somethi=
ng that you might outsource over time? Or there might be fleet builders?*

*BH:* Correct. So what we'll do, so just as we use the Aggregators to solve=
 the demand side, we will similarly use automation to solve the vendor side=
. So you will see us rocking up to a new city with whatever, a few hundred =
aircraft or 1,000 aircraft to a central depot or maintenance base where the=
 aircraft all live, and we will have contracts with all of the vendors in t=
hat city and that's it. We will stay in the center and the aircraft will go=
 out to those vendors and the vendors will load the cargo.

That's true scale, we won't do that today, but we will do that soon and tha=
t's where we have a city-based rollout model where we supply capacity to a =
city and those aircraft will just work for the city. They'll work for hospi=
tals, they'll work for restaurants, they'll work for coffee shops, whatever=
. But our job will be simply to supply that capacity to a population center=
 and the aircraft will do the rest and it's probably more software than the=
 hardware to do that. There's obviously safety on the hardware side and rel=
iability in the hardware side the rest of it is more like a Waymo, I think,=
 than a Tesla.

*What do cities look like in this future world dominated with your drones f=
lying everywhere overhead? One thing that's interesting that you said is th=
at actually strip malls are great for you, they have a lot of restaurants a=
nd they have a bunch of parking spots. What does the built environment look=
 like in 50 years, 60 years, once it's had time to change? Are restaurants =
gone? Everyone just delivers in? What does the future look like?*

*BH:* Well, I think it's the resurrection of the suburb. So suburban living=
 will have all the advantages of urban living. Get delivery in 10 minutes t=
o your house, get food delivered to your house and so we can fly food to yo=
ur house from anywhere in the whole city. You have every shop in the city y=
ou can get to your house even if you live in a suburb, so suburban living g=
ets better.

Do retail footprints change? I think they do. I think this whole idea of go=
ing out shopping around for things as an experience will still be there but=
 I think the functional getting that thing, the screwdriver, the spark plug=
, the hamburger, whatever it is, you shouldn't be getting into your car for=
 that, you shouldn't need to travel for that. So I think retailers, there w=
ill be an Amazon-ization that is much more viable in the suburbs now that i=
sn't now because Amazon need these gigantic big things with every product i=
n it. Whereas now we can aggregate that with the robots and that's the futu=
re.

But will there be more dark kitchens? Yes. Will restaurants look at the opp=
ortunity where right now they look at real estate to say, "I need to be whe=
re there's footfall, so I need to be in that strip mall because footfall"?

*Now, "I need a flat roof".*

*BH:* Yeah, exactly. I can be in a field so long as I have the product, and=
 so long as =E2=80=94 when we're mature, the only place you're going to com=
e to buy stuff is to us. It's like Amazon, right? But micro-local. So there=
fore, if you're a producer or a supplier of goods, you only need to think a=
bout, "How the hell do I get my thing into the drone?", and therefore, "I n=
eed to make sure I'm not on the high street and not covered by a big tree",=
 or basic stuff, that's it. A clear roof is probably the key requirement. B=
ut footfall and paying premium real estate prices for high footfall for man=
y vendors won't need to be a thing. They'll still be there, but there's opp=
ortunities to grow a food brand or any other brand for that matter in a fie=
ld on the edge of a population center and use the automation to get that pr=
oduct to your customers.

*Well, I think I learned a lot. This is super fascinating, we'll be watchin=
g with great interest. What series are you at as far as raising goes?*

*BH:* Series A. We've raised just over $60 million bucks so far, a tiny amo=
unt, and a small company still. But we're at the stage now where we are rea=
dy to grow, we want to start growing, so I think we'll start thinking about=
 this as growth rounds now where most of the capital goes into generating r=
evenue rather than building product.

*Right now, because you're pricing on transaction model you're very confide=
nt in your unit costs in every delivery. You're making a profit every time?=
*

*BH:* Correct. Every dollar we spend now, 70%, 80% of that will go into gen=
erating. So right now, every dollar you spend in this business produces thr=
ee-and-a-half dollars of annual revenue, and it's profitable. Every operati=
on we open is contribution positive year one. So it's nice, it's got a nice=
 profile to it, a little bit better than rolling out a Starbucks chain, but=
 with a much bigger moat.

*Amazing, amazing stuff. I'm glad you reached out. I will try to not make a=
ny more drone errors in the future, or maybe I will so that you'll ping me =
again and can see where things are.*

*BH:* I will indeed.

